const Q_CRK_2010=[{"id": "objective>CRK>2010>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What was God's purpose in creating man?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To be master of all creation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To help Him look after the garden</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To name the things He created</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To multiply and fill the earth</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Bible, specifically Genesis 1:26-28, God created man in His own image and gave him dominion over all other creatures. This implies that man was created to be master of all creation.</div>", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD :GOD AS CREATOR AND CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaac's prayer to God for his barren wife showed that he</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">truly loved her</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sincerely loved his God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had faith in God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was tired of being childless</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaac's prayer to God for his barren wife, as recorded in Genesis 25:21, is an act of faith. He believed in God's power to intervene in human situations, including barrenness. Therefore, this act showed his faith in God.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE : EXAMPLES OF ABRAHAM, HEBREW MIDWIVES AND DAVID"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In God's covenant with Israel, the central theme was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">restoration</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">circumcision</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">obedience</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">salvation</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, God's covenant with Israel was centered around obedience. God promised to bless Israel if they obeyed His laws and commandments. This is seen in several books of the Bible, including Exodus, Leviticus, and Deuteronomy. Therefore, the central theme of God's covenant with Israel was obedience.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Who am I that I should go to Pharaoh...\" <br/> When Moses resisted God's call with the statement above, it portrayed his</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stubbornness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">incompetence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lack of strength</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lack of eloquence</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Moses said, 'Who am I that I should go to Pharaoh...', he was expressing his feelings of inadequacy and lack of eloquence. He felt he was not a good speaker and would not be able to convince Pharaoh to let the Israelites go. This is seen in Exodus 4:10 where Moses said to the Lord, 'Pardon your servant, Lord. I have never been eloquent, neither in the past nor since you have spoken to your servant. I am slow of speech and tongue.' Therefore, this statement portrayed his lack of eloquence.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF MOSES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What was Samson's major achievement as Israel's leader?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He suppressed the Philistines</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He captured the city of Jericho</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He saved the Israelites from the Amorites</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He secured permanent independence for Israel</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samson's major achievement as Israel's leader was that he suppressed the Philistines. This is recorded in the Bible in the book of Judges chapters 13-16. Samson was a judge of Israel and he is known for his superhuman strength, which he used to fight against the Philistines, who were enemies of Israel at that time.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JUDGES - DEBORAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God guided the Israelites on their way from Egypt to the promised land by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the work of two angels</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dividing the Red Sea</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a pillar of cloud and a pillar of fire</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">miracles that gave them direction on the way</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Bible, in the book of Exodus, God guided the Israelites on their way from Egypt to the promised land by a pillar of cloud during the day and a pillar of fire during the night. These served as guides for the Israelites, showing them the direction they should go.</div>", "topic": "DIVINE PROVIDENCE, GUIDANCE AND PROTECTION :GUIDANCE AND PROTECTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Deal gently for my sake with the young man Absalom.\" <br/> David's statement above exhibited his</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indulgent love for his son</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">willingness to forgive his competitors</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">desire to punish Absalom himself</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">high level of parental control</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David's statement 'Deal gently for my sake with the young man Absalom' shows his indulgent love for his son Absalom. Despite Absalom's rebellion against him, David still cared for his son and did not want him to be harmed. This is a clear indication of his indulgent love for his son, not his willingness to forgive his competitors, desire to punish Absalom himself, or high level of parental control.</div>", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : DAVID"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">How did king Asa prove to be a godly king?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He killed all the prophets of Baal at Mount Carmel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He saved Judah from the Philistine menace</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He instituted spiritual reforms that removed all idols and prostitution in the land</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He made the worship of Yahweh mandatory for every Jew and sojourner</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">King Asa proved to be a godly king by instituting spiritual reforms that removed all idols and prostitution in the land. He was known for his religious reforms and efforts to rid his kingdom of idolatry and pagan practices. This is not about killing prophets of Baal at Mount Carmel, saving Judah from the Philistine menace, or making the worship of Yahweh mandatory for every Jew and sojourner.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Hebrew midwives who obeyed God rather than Pharaoh were blessed with</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">favour from all the Israelites</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">long life in Canaan</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resources</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">families</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Exodus 1:15-21, the Hebrew midwives, Shiphrah and Puah, feared God and did not do as the king of Egypt commanded them, but saved the male children alive. Therefore, God dealt well with the midwives and the people multiplied and grew very mighty. And because the midwives feared God, He provided households for them. So, the correct answer is 'families'.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE : EXAMPLES OF ABRAHAM, HEBREW MIDWIVES AND DAVID"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Saul disobeyed God's command, Samuel rebuked him by saying that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the sword would never depart from his house</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to obey was better than sacrifice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he should fear the LORD and obey the people's voice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">though he was little, yet he was the head</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Samuel 15:22, after Saul disobeyed God's command to completely destroy the Amalekites and their livestock, Samuel rebuked him by saying, 'Has the LORD as great delight in burnt offerings and sacrifices, as in obeying the voice of the LORD? Behold, to obey is better than sacrifice, and to listen than the fat of rams.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'to obey was better than sacrifice'.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE :EXAMPLES OF ADAM, COLLECTION OF MANNA, THE GOLDEN CALF, MOSES AND SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David's behaviour after Prophet Nathan accused him of murder and adultery showed his</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">justification</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">repentance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">greed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">righteousness</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David's behavior after Prophet Nathan accused him of murder and adultery showed his repentance. In the Bible, after Nathan confronted David about his sins, David confessed and repented. This is a demonstration of remorse and a desire to make amends, which is what repentance is about.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFTER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S REPENTANCE AND FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">How did King Solomon demonstrate his wisdom in setting the dispute over the ownership of a baby by the two prostitutes?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He interrogated them for seven days until the truth was discovered.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He interrogated them for only three days and the truth was revealed.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He asked them to divide the child into two and the mother was known.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He threatened to give the child to a neutral woman and the mother was known</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">King Solomon demonstrated his wisdom in settling the dispute over the ownership of a baby by the two prostitutes by suggesting to divide the child into two. This was a test to reveal the true mother who would rather lose the dispute than see her child killed. This is a demonstration of Solomon's wisdom in understanding human nature and using it to reveal the truth.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : THE WISDOM OF SOLOMON"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The prophet who made known the imminent division of the kingdom of Israel during Solomon's reign was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jehu</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ahijah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elisha</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The prophet who made known the imminent division of the kingdom of Israel during Solomon's reign was Ahijah. This is recorded in 1 Kings 11:29-31, where Ahijah the Shilonite prophesied to Jeroboam that he would become king over ten tribes of Israel.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : UNWISE POLICIES OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Naaman's leprosy was transferred to Gehazi because Gehazi was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ambitious</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">anxious</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">covetous</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">comtemptous</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Naaman's leprosy was transferred to Gehazi because Gehazi was covetous. This is recorded in 2 Kings 5:20-27, where Gehazi, the servant of Elisha, lied to Naaman to get gifts that Elisha had refused. When Elisha found out, he cursed Gehazi and his descendants with Naaman's leprosy.</div>", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Obadiah who was in charge of Ahab's household demonstrated reverence for the LORD by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">giving Elijah the bull for the sacrifice on Mount Carmel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rebuking Ahab and Jezebel for their evil deeds</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hiding a hundred prophets of God from Jezebel's wrath</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">helping Elijah to kill the prophets of Baal on Mount Carmel</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Obadiah demonstrated reverence for the LORD by hiding a hundred prophets of God from Jezebel's wrath. Jezebel was a queen who was known for her worship of Baal and her attempts to kill the prophets of God. Obadiah, however, feared the LORD greatly and when Jezebel cut off the prophets of the LORD, Obadiah took a hundred prophets and hid them by fifties in a cave, and fed them with bread and water (1 Kings 18:4).</div>", "topic": "THE SUPREMACY OF GOD : RELIGIOUS TENSION AND THE POWER OF GOD ON MOUNT CARMEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Although Josiah removed the vessels of Baal and Asherah from the Temple, God did not turn from the fierceness of His wrath because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people did not remove them completely</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jehoahaz, Josiah's had provoked Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Manasseh had provoked Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The people had opposed Josiah</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God did not turn from the fierceness of His wrath because Manasseh had provoked Him. Manasseh was a king of Judah who did evil in the sight of the LORD. He rebuilt the high places which his father Hezekiah had destroyed; he raised up altars for Baal, made a wooden image, as Ahab king of Israel had done, and worshipped all the host of heaven and served them (2 Kings 21:1-6). Despite Josiah's efforts to remove the vessels of Baal and Asherah from the Temple, the sins of Manasseh had provoked God's wrath against Judah.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What was Nehemiah's initial reaction to the news about the ruins of Jerusalem?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He tasked the people on what to contribute.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He called volunteers to assist him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He fasted and prayed for forgiveness of sins</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He asked for permission to travel home</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Nehemiah, when Nehemiah heard about the state of Jerusalem, his initial reaction was to fast and pray for the forgiveness of sins. He was deeply saddened by the news and turned to God in prayer, confessing the sins of the people of Israel and asking for God's mercy and help. This is recorded in Nehemiah 1:4-11.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">After the dedication of the Temple, Ezra studied the law of the LORD in order to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">defend the Jews against the Babylonians</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">become the first judge in Jerusalem</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">enhance his prophetic status</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">teach His status and ordinances in Israel</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ezra was a scribe and a priest who was deeply devoted to the law of the LORD. After the dedication of the Temple, Ezra studied the law not for personal gain or status, but to teach His statutes and ordinances in Israel. His aim was to educate the people about God's laws and to ensure that they were being followed. This is recorded in Ezra 7:10.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : RENEWAL OF THE COVENANT"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Daniel became distinguished above all other presidents and satraps because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an excellent spirit was in him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the spirit of Darius was in him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he was a good administrator</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he was highly educated</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Daniel 6:3, it is stated that Daniel became distinguished above all other presidents and satraps because an excellent spirit was in him. This means that Daniel had a unique character and wisdom that set him apart from others.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JOSEPH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">How did the Ninevites react to Jonah's message?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They did not believe it</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They believed it for a while</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They repented of their sins</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They ordered him out of their city</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Jonah 3:5-10, it is stated that the Ninevites believed Jonah's message and repented of their sins. They declared a fast, and all of them, from the greatest to the least, put on sackcloth to show their repentance.</div>", "topic": "GOD'S MESSAGE TO NINEVEH: JONAH AND HIS MESSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Prophet Hosea's analysis, harlotry is equivalent to Israel's</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prostitution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">idolatrous practices</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">religious practices</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adultery</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Hosea, the prophet Hosea uses the metaphor of harlotry to describe Israel's idolatrous practices. Harlotry in this context is symbolic of Israel's unfaithfulness to God through idol worship.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : CONDITION OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"...But let justice roll down like waters and righteousness like an overflowing stream.\"  <br/> Amos' statement above suggests that the society was terribly</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vindictive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abusive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oppressive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">destructive</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement by Amos is a call for justice and righteousness, suggesting that the society was oppressive. The imagery of justice rolling down like waters and righteousness like an overflowing stream indicates a desire for a significant and overwhelming change in the society.</div>", "topic": "SOCIAL JUSTICE, TRUE RELIGION AND DIVINE LOVE:SOCIAL JUSTICE AND TRUE RELIGION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah emphasized holiness above all things because God</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">knew their hearts were right with him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was not interested in their sacrifices</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">who called them is holy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was searching their sinful hearts</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah emphasized holiness above all things because God who called them is holy. This is based on the biblical principle that God is holy and those who serve Him must also be holy. The concept of holiness in this context refers to being set apart for God's service, living a life that is pleasing to God, and avoiding sin.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF ISAIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God told Ezekiel that the house of Israel would not listen to him because they</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were a people of foreign speech</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had forsaken His laws</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were of a stubborn heart</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had not truly repented</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God told Ezekiel that the house of Israel would not listen to him because they were of a stubborn heart. This is based on the biblical account where God describes the Israelites as a rebellious and stubborn people who have turned away from His commands. The concept of a 'stubborn heart' in this context refers to a state of being resistant to God's word and unwilling to obey His commands.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF EZEKIEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Isaiah, God sent him to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Proclaim liberty to the captives</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">proclaim victory over Israel's enemies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be a watchman over Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">destroy and overthrow nations</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the book of Isaiah, specifically Isaiah 61:1, God sent Isaiah to 'proclaim liberty to the captives'. This was part of Isaiah's mission to bring good news to the poor and bind up the brokenhearted.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF ISAIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus was tempted by the devil so as to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fulfil all righteousness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">show His power over forces of nature</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">show that no one is above temptation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">test the devil's power</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The temptation of Jesus by the devil as recorded in Matthew 4:1-11 was not to fulfill all righteousness, show His power over forces of nature, or test the devil's power. Rather, it was to show that Jesus, though being divine, was also human and subject to temptation, yet without sin. This demonstrates that no one, not even the Son of God, is above temptation.</div>", "topic": "THE BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATIONS OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Depart from me, for I am a sinful man, O Lord.\"  <br/> This statement was uttered by Peter at the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">last supper</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">garden of Gethsemane</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">call of the disciples</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">transfiguration</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Depart from me, for I am a sinful man, O Lord.\" was uttered by Peter at the call of the disciples. This happened when Jesus performed a miracle by catching a large number of fish after Peter and his partners had toiled all night and caught nothing. Peter was astonished and overwhelmed by the miracle, and he recognized his own sinfulness in the presence of Jesus, hence the statement.</div>", "topic": "DISCIPLESHIP : THE CALL OF THE FIRST DISCIPLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The impact of Jesus' miracle of turning water into wine was that the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">servants were astonished</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">master of ceremony believed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disciples believed more in Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">people glorified God</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The impact of Jesus' miracle of turning water into wine was that the disciples believed more in Him. This miracle, which is recorded in John 2:1-11, was the first of Jesus' signs through which He revealed His glory, and His disciples believed in Him. The miracle demonstrated Jesus' divine authority and power, confirming their faith in Him as the Messiah.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : NATURE MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">After the healing of the demoniac in the country of the Gerasenes, the people begged Jesus to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stay with them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">visit them always</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">go away from them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">heal their sick</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of Luke 8:37, after Jesus healed the demon-possessed man in the region of the Gerasenes, the people were overcome with fear and asked Jesus to leave their region. Therefore, the correct answer is 'go away from them'.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : EXORCISM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus told the parable of the lost sheep in order to illustrate that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">every believer ought to rejoice with those who rejoice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">no person can hide from God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's love is unlimited</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there is joy in heaven over sinner who repents</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable of the lost sheep, found in Luke 15:1-7, is a story told by Jesus to illustrate the joy in heaven when a sinner repents and turns back to God. Therefore, the correct answer is 'there is joy in heaven over a sinner who repents'.</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES ABOUT LOVE OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Jesus, the seventy disciples should rejoice because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their names were written in heaven</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their faith and zeal were increased</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of the submission of evil spirits to them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of the fall of Satan from heaven like lightening</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in Luke 10:20, Jesus told the seventy disciples to rejoice because their names were written in heaven. This was after they returned from their mission, excited that even demons submitted to them in Jesus' name. Jesus acknowledged their success but pointed out that the greater cause for joy was their secure relationship with God.</div>", "topic": "MISSION OF THE DISCIPLES : THE MISSION OF THE SEVENTY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Mark, after the transfiguration, Jesus charged His disciples to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be prepared for persecution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tell no one what they had seen</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have no hands in His betrayal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">go to the Gentiles immediately</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Mark 9:9, after the transfiguration, Jesus gave His disciples orders not to tell anyone what they had seen until the Son of Man had risen from the dead. The transfiguration was a significant event where Jesus' divine glory was revealed, but He wanted to keep it a secret until after His resurrection to fully understand the event in the light of His death and resurrection.</div>", "topic": "THE TRANSFIGURATION : THE EVENTS LEADING TO THE TRANSFIGURATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Luke, the multitude that followed Jesus during the triumphal entry rejoiced and praised God with a loud voice because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they realized that Jesus was a prophet</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of the mighty works He had done</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was riding on a colt in humility</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they believed He was their Messiah</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Luke 19:37, it is stated that the multitude praised God joyfully with a loud voice for all the mighty works they had seen. This indicates that their praise was a result of the mighty works Jesus had done, not necessarily because they realized He was a prophet, He was riding on a colt in humility, or they believed He was their Messiah.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE : TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Truly, I say to you, today you will be with me in paradise.\" <br/> Jesus made the statement above to one of the criminals because he</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">respected Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">praised Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rebuked his partner</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was repentant</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Luke 23:39-43, one of the criminals hanging beside Jesus rebuked the other criminal and acknowledged his own sinfulness, showing repentance. He then asked Jesus to remember him when He comes into His kingdom. In response to this, Jesus told him, \"Truly, I say to you, today you will be with me in paradise.\" This shows that the criminal was repentant, not merely because he respected, praised Jesus or rebuked his partner.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The message of the risen Christ to the women who came early to the tomb was to be relayed to the disciples and</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Jews</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Sadducees</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Thomas</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in Matthew 28:7, the risen Christ instructed the women who came early to the tomb to go and tell his disciples that he has risen from the dead and that they will see him in Galilee. Among the disciples, Peter was specifically mentioned, hence the correct answer is Peter.</div>", "topic": "RESURRECTION, APPEARANCES AND ASCENSION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION AND APPEARANCE OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Gospel of John, Jesus is the true vine while the vine dresser is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Holy Spirit</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His father</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the gardener</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His mother</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Gospel of John, specifically in John 15:1, Jesus refers to himself as the true vine and his Father as the gardener or the vine dresser. This metaphor is used to illustrate the relationship between God the Father (the vine dresser), Jesus (the vine), and believers (the branches). The vine dresser takes care of the vine and prunes the branches to make them bear more fruit, just as God takes care of believers and sometimes disciplines them to make them more fruitful.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE TRUE VINE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"...Why has Satan filled your heart to lie to the Holy Spirit...\" <br/> Peter rebuked Ananias in the statement above for his sin of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">greed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">insincerity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">covetousness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">partiality</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The sin of Ananias, as described in the book of Acts in the Bible, was greed. Ananias and his wife Sapphira sold a piece of property and kept back part of the proceeds for themselves, while pretending to give all of it to the church. Peter rebuked them for lying to the Holy Spirit, which was a manifestation of their greed.</div>", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH : PROBLEMS OF COMMUNAL LIVING AND SOLUTIONS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul informed the Galatians that the gospel he preached came through</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a revelation of Jesus Christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his desire to lead them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inspiration from the angels</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the faith of men</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Galatians 1:11-12, Paul states that the gospel he preached was not of human origin. He did not receive it from any man, nor was he taught it; rather, he received it by revelation from Jesus Christ. Therefore, the correct answer is 'a revelation of Jesus Christ'.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE COMMISSIONING AND MISSION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"You son of the devil, you enemy of all righteousness, full of all deceit and villainy...\" <br/> The statement of Paul was addressed to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elymas, the magician</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paulus, the proconsul</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Simon, the magician</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Demetrius, the silversmith</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Acts 13:6-12, Paul and Barnabas encountered a Jewish sorcerer and false prophet named Bar-Jesus, also known as Elymas. When Elymas tried to turn the proconsul, Sergius Paulus, away from the faith, Paul rebuked him and called him 'You son of the devil, you enemy of all righteousness, full of all deceit and villainy.' Therefore, the statement was addressed to Elymas, the magician.</div>", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE : PERSECUTION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"...Unless you are circumcised according to the custom of Moses, you cannot be saved.\"  <br/> The statement above by the men from Judea lead to the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">murmurs of the Hellenists</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">convening of the Jerusalem Council</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">persecution that scattered the disciples</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">circumcision of the Gentiles</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement 'Unless you are circumcised according to the custom of Moses, you cannot be saved' was made by certain men from Judea who came down to Antioch. This statement caused a great dispute and debate among the believers, leading to the convening of the Jerusalem Council to discuss this matter. This event is recorded in Acts 15:1-2.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE COUNCIL OF JERUSALEM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Galatians, the Law was added because of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">righteousness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">transgressions</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">grace</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">persecution</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Galatians 3:19, the Law was added because of transgressions. The Law was given to make people aware of sin and its consequences. It served as a guide to show people their sins and to lead them to Christ.</div>", "topic": "THE LAW AND GRACE : THE PLACE OF THE LAW AMONG THE JEWS."}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Galatians, the death of Christ has eliminated all forms of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">suffering</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">difference</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">condemnation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">poverty</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Galatians 3:28, the death of Christ has eliminated all forms of difference. In Christ, there is no Jew or Greek, slave or free, male or female. All are one in Christ Jesus. This means that the death of Christ has broken down the barriers and differences that separate people.</div>", "topic": "THE LAW AND GRACE : THE PURPOSE AND SIGNIFICANCE OF THE LAW AND GRACE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter in his teaching on humility, admonishes Christians should re-affirm their love for those who</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">safeguard their faith</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seek things that are above</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be gentle in spirit</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">avoid life's anxiety</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In his teachings, Peter emphasized the importance of humility and gentleness in spirit. He encouraged Christians to show love and kindness to everyone, regardless of their actions or attitudes. This is in line with the Christian teaching of 'love your neighbor as yourself'.</div>", "topic": "HUMILITY : MEANING AND REQUIREMENTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul in Corinthians advised that Christians should re-affirm their love for those who</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are kind to them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wrong them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">humble themselves</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are in authority</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Corinthians, Paul advised Christians to reaffirm their love for those who wrong them. This is in line with the Christian teaching of forgiveness and love. Christians are encouraged to forgive those who wrong them and to show them love, as a reflection of God's love for humanity.</div>", "topic": "FORGIVENESS : PAUL’S TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Corinthians, variety of gifts are inspired by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fervent prayers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">angels of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">constant fasting</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the same Spirit</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Corinthians 12:4-6, there are different kinds of gifts, but the same Spirit distributes them. Therefore, the variety of gifts are inspired by the same Spirit, not by fervent prayers, angels of God, or constant fasting.</div>", "topic": "SPIRITUAL GIFTS : THE DIFFERENT SPIRITUAL GIFTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Paul in Corinthians, generosity produces</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">righteousness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">salvation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the grace of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">thanksgiving to God</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 2 Corinthians 9:11-12, Paul states that generosity results in thanksgiving to God. This is because the generosity of believers not only meets the needs of the saints but also overflows in many thanksgivings to God. Therefore, according to Paul, generosity produces thanksgiving to God, not righteousness, salvation, or the grace of God.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIAN GIVING : THE IMPORTANCE OF CHRISTIAN GIVING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Busy bodies and those living in idleness in the church at Thessalonica were admonished to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pray for those in authority for peace</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">do their work in quietness and earn a living</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">appeal to those in authority to create jobs</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">endure persecution from their masters</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in 2 Thessalonians 3:11-12, Paul admonishes those who are idle and disruptive and not busy at work but busybodies. He commands them to settle down and earn the food they eat. Therefore, the correct answer is 'do their work in quietness and earn a living'.</div>", "topic": "DIGNITY OF LABOUR : BENEFITS OF DIGNITY OF LABOUR"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul in Thessalonians told believers that the coming of the Lord would be accompanied by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">songs of praise</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the sound of the trumpet</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">signs and wonders</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wailing and mourning</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Thessalonians 4:16, Paul describes the coming of the Lord, saying 'For the Lord himself will come down from heaven, with a loud command, with the voice of the archangel and with the trumpet call of God, and the dead in Christ will rise first.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'the sound of the trumpet'.</div>", "topic": "THE SECOND COMING OF CHRIST : THE SIGNS OF THE COMING OF CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">James stated in his epistle that when believers met various trails, their faith produces</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">weakness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">strength</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">steadfastness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">righteousness</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of James, specifically James 1:2-4, it is stated that when believers face various trials, the testing of their faith produces steadfastness (or perseverance). This means that going through trials helps believers to become more resilient and steadfast in their faith.</div>", "topic": "FAITH, COURAGE AND PROTECTION : EXAMPLES OF DANIEL, SHADRACH, MESHACH AND ABEDNEGO"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2010>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter in his epistle enjoined servants to be submissive to their masters with all</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gentleness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seriousness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">respect</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">humility</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Peter 2:18, Peter instructs servants (or slaves) to be submissive to their masters with all respect. This means that servants should show proper respect and obedience to their masters, regardless of whether they are good and gentle or harsh.</div>", "topic": "HUMILITY : MEANING AND REQUIREMENTS"}];
